1
00:00:04,922 --> 00:00:07,424
<i>The cutest neighborhood in the world,</i>
<i>Kangho-dong.</i>

2
00:00:08,717 --> 00:00:10,302
<i>In the world</i>

3
00:00:10,385 --> 00:00:12,804
The customer should be here by now.

4
00:00:17,935 --> 00:00:23,941
SECOND BOOK: <i>ABOUT DEATH</i>

5
00:00:24,942 --> 00:00:28,195
Books really are food for the soul.

6
00:00:30,364 --> 00:00:31,657
I want food for the body too though.

7
00:00:34,785 --> 00:00:36,161
Hello.

8
00:00:36,245 --> 00:00:38,372
Oh, my! It's you!

9
00:00:39,206 --> 00:00:41,291
- The guest who made the reservation.
- That's me.

10
00:00:41,375 --> 00:00:42,876
- This way, please.
- Oh, my.

11
00:00:43,502 --> 00:00:45,087
- Hello.
- Ho-dong.

12
00:00:45,504 --> 00:00:46,421
Sorry? Do you know me?

13
00:00:46,797 --> 00:00:48,215
- Yes, hi.
- Come in.

14
00:00:48,298 --> 00:00:49,967
LEE SUN-BIN, ACTOR
Have a seat.

15
00:00:50,050 --> 00:00:51,176
You're here to sell a book, right?

16
00:00:51,260 --> 00:00:52,761
- I am.
- Right.

17
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:55,347
Before you sell the book to us,

18
00:00:55,430 --> 00:00:57,432
- let me introduce this place.
- Of course.

19
00:00:57,516 --> 00:01:00,352
This is a space
where people are read like books,

20
00:01:00,435 --> 00:01:03,480
located in the cutest neighborhood
in the world, Kangho-dong,

21
00:01:03,564 --> 00:01:06,483
called Hodong's Bookshop. Welcome!

22
00:01:06,567 --> 00:01:08,652
Hello, thank you.

23
00:01:10,153 --> 00:01:11,905
It is a bit shocking.

24
00:01:11,989 --> 00:01:13,115
- To see me?
- Yes.

25
00:01:13,198 --> 00:01:14,449
Do you know my name?

26
00:01:14,825 --> 00:01:17,077
- Hocrates.
- That's right.

27
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:18,704
Socrates was my mentor.

28
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:20,539
- I know, I heard.
- Yes.

29
00:01:20,622 --> 00:01:22,541
- I asked too many questions.
- Right.

30
00:01:22,624 --> 00:01:24,334
- So you were kicked out.
- Yes.

31
00:01:24,459 --> 00:01:26,378
I've been wandering for 2,000 years.

32
00:01:28,380 --> 00:01:30,173
- What do you think?
- I think

33
00:01:30,257 --> 00:01:32,759
you look super cute.

34
00:01:33,010 --> 00:01:34,928
I'm flustered by how cute you look.

35
00:01:35,012 --> 00:01:36,263
- Do you mean it?
- Yes.

36
00:01:36,555 --> 00:01:37,806
- You know what?
- Yes?

37
00:01:38,390 --> 00:01:39,641
What an "acute" observation.

38
00:01:39,725 --> 00:01:40,809
"Acute"?

39
00:01:40,892 --> 00:01:46,398
FOOTNOTE:
HOCRATES LIKES BEING CALLED "CUTE"

40
00:01:47,149 --> 00:01:49,860
I'm over 2,000 years old,
and I opened a bookshop.

41
00:01:49,943 --> 00:01:51,695
- Wow, congratulations.
- Thank you.

42
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,363
The shop looks beautiful from the outside.

43
00:01:54,197 --> 00:01:55,866
- You're here to sell.
- I am.

44
00:01:55,949 --> 00:01:57,659
In this bookshop,

45
00:01:57,743 --> 00:02:00,329
- we don't accept cash or cards.
- I see.

46
00:02:00,412 --> 00:02:02,789
- We only accept stories.
- Only stories. I see.

47
00:02:03,165 --> 00:02:05,626
Today, we'll read the book of Lee Sun-bin,

48
00:02:06,209 --> 00:02:08,545
then we'll set a price for the book.

49
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:09,921
That's beautiful.

50
00:02:10,005 --> 00:02:12,132
"Read the book of Lee Sun-bin."

51
00:02:13,383 --> 00:02:15,510
I'm 200% a "Feeling" type in MBTI.

52
00:02:15,594 --> 00:02:16,887
I see.

53
00:02:17,387 --> 00:02:18,430
So am I.

54
00:02:18,972 --> 00:02:20,265
I am. What?

55
00:02:21,433 --> 00:02:22,726
I'm an ESFP.

56
00:02:25,604 --> 00:02:27,481
I only know that I'm an "F."

57
00:02:27,564 --> 00:02:29,149
- That's all you know?
- Yes.

58
00:02:29,232 --> 00:02:31,276
FOOTNOTE:
HOCRATES' MBTI TYPE IS SAID TO BE INFP

59
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:32,486
- Okay, first of all,
- Yes?

60
00:02:32,569 --> 00:02:34,029
what's your official name?

61
00:02:34,112 --> 00:02:36,031
It's Lee Sun-bin.

62
00:02:36,114 --> 00:02:37,949
<i>"Sun"</i> as in "first," <i>"bin"</i> as in "shine."

63
00:02:38,033 --> 00:02:39,326
It means "shine first."

64
00:02:39,409 --> 00:02:41,620
- So you can shine bright?
- Yes.

65
00:02:42,537 --> 00:02:43,497
What do you do?

66
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:44,956
I act for a living.

67
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:46,958
- You're an actor?
- Yes, I act.

68
00:02:48,126 --> 00:02:49,920
Are you sure your job isn't an angel?

69
00:02:57,427 --> 00:02:58,553
Wait...

70
00:02:59,054 --> 00:03:00,263
That was scary.

71
00:03:00,347 --> 00:03:02,182
FOOTNOTE: HOCRATES IS AN INFP
AND LIKES BEING CALLED "CUTE"

72
00:03:02,265 --> 00:03:04,059
I thought you were an angel.

73
00:03:04,142 --> 00:03:06,061
No, you got that wrong.

74
00:03:06,144 --> 00:03:07,270
- Did I?
- Yes.

75
00:03:07,354 --> 00:03:09,731
We'll find out eventually.

76
00:03:09,815 --> 00:03:12,067
Before we get into it,

77
00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:13,819
what book are you here to sell?

78
00:03:14,736 --> 00:03:15,946
To be honest,

79
00:03:16,029 --> 00:03:19,199
I'm not that well-versed in books.

80
00:03:19,282 --> 00:03:22,661
- But I love webtoons.
- I see.

81
00:03:22,744 --> 00:03:24,663
So I brought one published as a book.

82
00:03:24,746 --> 00:03:27,249
It's called<i> About Death</i>.

83
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:29,167
Yes.

84
00:03:29,251 --> 00:03:30,460
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

85
00:03:31,002 --> 00:03:33,338
LEE SUN-BIN'S FAVORITE BOOK: <i>ABOUT DEATH</i>

86
00:03:33,422 --> 00:03:35,882
STORY BY SINI, ILLUSTRATED BY HYUNO

87
00:03:35,966 --> 00:03:38,301
A COLLECTED EDITION
OF THE 2012 NAVER WEBTOON

88
00:03:39,761 --> 00:03:42,931
CHARACTERS WHO DIED
MEET A GOD IN THE FORM OF AN ORDINARY MAN,

89
00:03:43,014 --> 00:03:44,516
TALK ABOUT THEIR LIVES,

90
00:03:44,599 --> 00:03:46,727
AND GAIN INSIGHT ON LIFE

91
00:03:46,810 --> 00:03:49,855
THE WEBTOON GAINED MUCH ATTENTION
WITH ITS SIMPLE STYLE

92
00:03:49,938 --> 00:03:51,273
AND EMOTIONAL STORYTELLING

93
00:03:51,940 --> 00:03:54,443
This has three volumes?

94
00:03:54,526 --> 00:03:55,402
That's right.

95
00:03:55,485 --> 00:03:58,071
I've always wanted
to recommend this to people.

96
00:03:58,155 --> 00:04:00,532
What is <i>About Death</i> about?

97
00:04:00,699 --> 00:04:01,908
<i>About Death</i>.

98
00:04:01,992 --> 00:04:04,161
It makes you think about life and death

99
00:04:04,244 --> 00:04:06,121
not just from your own perspective,

100
00:04:06,204 --> 00:04:10,250
- but from so many different perspectives.
- I see.

101
00:04:10,333 --> 00:04:12,377
I first started

102
00:04:12,461 --> 00:04:14,713
reading this webtoon on my phone.

103
00:04:14,796 --> 00:04:17,799
At first, I clicked because
the illustration was unique.

104
00:04:17,883 --> 00:04:20,510
Thumbnails give you
a certain impression, right?

105
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:23,930
- They do.
- They are really important for webtoons.

106
00:04:24,014 --> 00:04:26,600
Not only the likability
of the illustration,

107
00:04:26,683 --> 00:04:29,227
but also the thumbnails
play important roles in a webtoon.

108
00:04:29,311 --> 00:04:31,563
And when I was reading the webtoon,

109
00:04:31,646 --> 00:04:35,150
it was one of those with background music.

110
00:04:35,233 --> 00:04:37,152
When you press the music button,

111
00:04:37,235 --> 00:04:40,363
a different soundtrack plays
for each episode.

112
00:04:41,031 --> 00:04:43,116
So when you're reading the webtoon,

113
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:44,910
it feels as if you're watching a film
with a soundtrack.

114
00:04:45,535 --> 00:04:46,870
So you turn the music on--

115
00:04:46,953 --> 00:04:48,580
Like you're listening to
the soundtrack of the story.

116
00:04:48,663 --> 00:04:51,750
Yes, and I was totally hooked
because of it.

117
00:04:52,125 --> 00:04:56,087
- I'm an actor,
- Right.

118
00:04:56,171 --> 00:04:57,589
so when I'm rehearsing lines,

119
00:04:57,672 --> 00:05:00,675
and I don't know
who I'll be acting with yet,

120
00:05:00,759 --> 00:05:03,220
- or I have to rehearse all alone,
- You need imagination.

121
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:04,805
in those cases,

122
00:05:04,888 --> 00:05:07,766
whether it's a rom-com
or a different genre,

123
00:05:07,849 --> 00:05:09,309
I imagine the soundtrack
that fits the genre...

124
00:05:09,392 --> 00:05:10,977
- Yes, like background music.
- I imagine...

125
00:05:11,061 --> 00:05:12,646
Exactly, like background music.

126
00:05:12,729 --> 00:05:14,898
If I imagine the music that'd be playing
during those scenes,

127
00:05:14,981 --> 00:05:17,234
- it helps a lot in rehearsing my lines.
- I see.

128
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:19,402
That's a habit I have.

129
00:05:19,486 --> 00:05:20,654
That's why the fact

130
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:23,865
that every episode of this webtoon
had a soundtrack

131
00:05:23,949 --> 00:05:25,283
meant so much to me.

132
00:05:25,367 --> 00:05:27,285
It wouldn't have been
as meaningful without it,

133
00:05:27,369 --> 00:05:30,622
but the music amplified all the emotions.

134
00:05:30,997 --> 00:05:33,041
That's what got me hooked.

135
00:05:33,124 --> 00:05:35,669
I read every episode over and over again.

136
00:05:35,752 --> 00:05:39,631
But that wasn't enough,
so I bought the physical copy.

137
00:05:40,757 --> 00:05:42,092
This is in three volumes,

138
00:05:42,175 --> 00:05:46,179
but the two-volume version
came with a CD of the soundtracks.

139
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:47,180
THE FIRST EDITION INCLUDED AN OST CD

140
00:05:47,264 --> 00:05:49,391
So at home, I put that in my CD player

141
00:05:49,933 --> 00:05:50,934
and read the books.

142
00:05:51,309 --> 00:05:52,602
As I understand it,

143
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:54,563
this book is not 100%

144
00:05:54,646 --> 00:05:56,606
- just about death.
- No, it's not.

145
00:05:56,690 --> 00:05:58,942
It's about many different people

146
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:03,405
who are in different situations,
and their lives and deaths.

147
00:06:03,488 --> 00:06:06,867
It's a detailed story
about life and death.

148
00:06:07,242 --> 00:06:08,577
So some parts are relatable,

149
00:06:08,660 --> 00:06:10,453
and others are mind-baffling.

150
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:14,124
One thing that's so obvious
but I'd never thought about

151
00:06:14,749 --> 00:06:17,711
is that death can't exist without life.

152
00:06:18,461 --> 00:06:20,714
That hit me hard.

153
00:06:20,797 --> 00:06:23,174
Because this book is called <i>About Death</i>,

154
00:06:23,258 --> 00:06:26,720
- you'd think it's all about death.
- Right.

155
00:06:26,803 --> 00:06:29,222
But on the contrary,

156
00:06:29,306 --> 00:06:32,893
it makes you
think about life on a deeper level.

157
00:06:32,976 --> 00:06:34,895
If this weren't a webtoon,

158
00:06:34,978 --> 00:06:36,563
and you actually...

159
00:06:38,398 --> 00:06:40,817
- It's not pleasant, but let's imagine.
- Okay.

160
00:06:40,901 --> 00:06:43,320
If you actually met a god,
how would you feel?

161
00:06:43,403 --> 00:06:44,946
I think I'd be scared.

162
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:47,574
I'd be really scared.

163
00:06:48,450 --> 00:06:50,452
- Music.
- There's music?

164
00:06:53,788 --> 00:06:55,373
- Can you hear it?
- I can.

165
00:06:59,377 --> 00:07:00,921
- Imagine.
- Okay.

166
00:07:11,598 --> 00:07:13,224
I think it's too small for you.

167
00:07:13,725 --> 00:07:14,935
Hold on.

168
00:07:15,018 --> 00:07:19,564
FOOTNOTE: THE STYLE HOCRATES WAS GOING FOR

169
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:24,444
Hello.

170
00:07:25,654 --> 00:07:26,988
I am a god.

171
00:07:29,115 --> 00:07:30,575
Do you know where you are?

172
00:07:31,576 --> 00:07:33,912
Am I dead?

173
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:42,796
Not yet.

174
00:07:44,464 --> 00:07:45,548
You're not dead yet.

175
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:50,595
Anyway,

176
00:07:50,679 --> 00:07:52,138
I think it would be scary.

177
00:07:52,597 --> 00:07:55,100
It's someone you want to meet,
but don't want to at the same time.

178
00:07:55,183 --> 00:07:56,267
That's right.

179
00:07:56,434 --> 00:07:58,019
My build is nothing like his.

180
00:07:58,103 --> 00:08:01,189
The cardigan is too small for you.

181
00:08:02,857 --> 00:08:05,068
You brought the book, <i>About Death</i>,

182
00:08:05,151 --> 00:08:06,569
but now it's time to read

183
00:08:06,653 --> 00:08:08,154
- the book of Lee Sun-bin.
- Yes.

184
00:08:08,947 --> 00:08:12,158
"Lee Sun-bin, you have played
the roles of many different lives.

185
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:14,995
But today, I want to hear about your life.

186
00:08:15,537 --> 00:08:19,207
Let's hear your story
so we won't be so bored on our way."

187
00:08:19,791 --> 00:08:21,001
That's a great quote.

188
00:08:21,376 --> 00:08:23,294
That's such a great quote!

189
00:08:24,921 --> 00:08:28,508
Most characters facing death
in <i>About Death</i>

190
00:08:28,591 --> 00:08:31,136
- Yes?
- have deep regrets about their lives.

191
00:08:31,469 --> 00:08:32,512
Why is that?

192
00:08:32,595 --> 00:08:35,640
Probably because it was nothing
like the death they'd pictured.

193
00:08:35,724 --> 00:08:38,768
- I thought that was the reason.
- I think so, too.

194
00:08:39,227 --> 00:08:41,396
Was your dream...

195
00:08:41,479 --> 00:08:42,480
SUN-BIN'S DREAM
FOR AN END WITH NO REGRETS?

196
00:08:42,564 --> 00:08:43,648
...always to be an actor?

197
00:08:43,732 --> 00:08:46,943
No, I didn't always
dream of becoming an actor.

198
00:08:47,652 --> 00:08:50,739
Your dream wasn't to be
an actor from the beginning?

199
00:08:50,822 --> 00:08:52,198
No, it wasn't.

200
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:55,785
I didn't know
what I wanted to do at the time,

201
00:08:55,869 --> 00:08:58,872
but I had a great opportunity to audition.

202
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:01,666
So I started doing musicals
at the theater company, Hakchon.

203
00:09:01,750 --> 00:09:03,835
- Hakchon is well-known.
- I know.

204
00:09:03,918 --> 00:09:07,881
It's the home
of many famous Korean actors.

205
00:09:07,964 --> 00:09:10,925
- I know.
- Can you name a few?

206
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:13,303
There's Hwang Jung-min,

207
00:09:13,386 --> 00:09:15,096
Kim Yun-seok,

208
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:16,473
and Sul Kyung-gu.

209
00:09:16,556 --> 00:09:18,475
Hwang Jung-min and I were

210
00:09:18,558 --> 00:09:20,226
classmates in middle school.

211
00:09:20,643 --> 00:09:21,686
No way!

212
00:09:21,770 --> 00:09:23,605
Wait, no. I'm 2,000 years old. Never mind.

213
00:09:23,688 --> 00:09:24,981
- Oh, right.
- Yes.

214
00:09:25,482 --> 00:09:26,900
FOOTNOTE: HOCRATES IN MIDDLE SCHOOL

215
00:09:26,983 --> 00:09:29,235
- At one point in those 2,000 years,
- Yes.

216
00:09:29,319 --> 00:09:30,779
you went to school with him.

217
00:09:30,862 --> 00:09:31,780
I did, yes.

218
00:09:31,863 --> 00:09:33,698
I see.

219
00:09:34,157 --> 00:09:37,243
Did you have to audition to join Hakchon?
Or was that unnecessary?

220
00:09:37,327 --> 00:09:38,369
You have to audition.

221
00:09:38,453 --> 00:09:39,496
- You have to?
- Yes.

222
00:09:39,579 --> 00:09:42,957
The auditions were not open
to high school students

223
00:09:43,041 --> 00:09:44,334
for Hakchon's plays.

224
00:09:44,417 --> 00:09:45,710
- Right?
- But at the time,

225
00:09:45,794 --> 00:09:48,671
they were going to put on a musical

226
00:09:48,755 --> 00:09:51,549
about a high school kid's
teenage rebellion.

227
00:09:51,633 --> 00:09:55,095
And they wanted to see
an actual high schooler playing the role.

228
00:09:55,178 --> 00:09:58,723
So they opened the audition up
to high school students.

229
00:09:58,807 --> 00:10:01,726
That's when I went to audition.

230
00:10:01,810 --> 00:10:04,062
I didn't know anything about acting.

231
00:10:04,145 --> 00:10:05,730
I'd never taken any classes.

232
00:10:05,814 --> 00:10:07,774
I just heard there was an opportunity,

233
00:10:07,857 --> 00:10:11,069
and even though
I was sure I wouldn't get it,

234
00:10:11,152 --> 00:10:13,571
I was brave enough to apply.

235
00:10:13,655 --> 00:10:14,989
So I practiced

236
00:10:15,365 --> 00:10:17,242
and showcased my terrible acting

237
00:10:17,325 --> 00:10:19,619
in that intimidating setting.

238
00:10:20,036 --> 00:10:21,412
I just gave it a shot.

239
00:10:21,788 --> 00:10:24,666
What did you actually learn at Hakchon?

240
00:10:24,749 --> 00:10:28,670
I didn't know how to do anything.

241
00:10:28,753 --> 00:10:30,839
I learned how to do everything there,

242
00:10:30,922 --> 00:10:34,467
like vocal techniques,
diction, and warm-ups.

243
00:10:34,884 --> 00:10:37,011
I copied whatever everyone else was doing.

244
00:10:37,095 --> 00:10:40,348
I didn't get the part
for the high school rebellion musical

245
00:10:40,431 --> 00:10:43,101
that I applied for,

246
00:10:43,184 --> 00:10:45,645
but they asked if I wanted to be
the lead in a play for kids.

247
00:10:45,728 --> 00:10:47,772
- They suggested I take that role.
- See?

248
00:10:47,856 --> 00:10:50,692
It was a play for children,
but they made me the lead.

249
00:10:50,775 --> 00:10:52,360
So I became an actor.

250
00:10:52,443 --> 00:10:53,403
- At Hakchon.
- Yes.

251
00:10:53,486 --> 00:10:54,779
THE LEAD OF
<i>THE INVINCIBLE THREE MUSKETEERS</i>

252
00:10:54,863 --> 00:10:56,072
Yes,

253
00:10:56,156 --> 00:10:57,615
but in my last year of high school,

254
00:10:57,699 --> 00:11:00,368
I was told I risked being held back
since I skipped too many classes.

255
00:11:00,451 --> 00:11:02,704
I had to stop doing musicals
and go to school.

256
00:11:02,787 --> 00:11:04,998
So I did in my second and third year.

257
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:07,542
I couldn't do musicals,
even though I just found my dream.

258
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:10,420
I thought I could just keep doing it.

259
00:11:10,503 --> 00:11:12,422
- But you couldn't.
- I risked being held back in school,

260
00:11:12,505 --> 00:11:14,340
so I couldn't do any plays.

261
00:11:14,424 --> 00:11:17,594
So I worked part-time jobs
while practicing,

262
00:11:17,677 --> 00:11:20,388
and when I got paid,

263
00:11:20,471 --> 00:11:21,764
I just ran away from home.

264
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:24,517
It's not an example
students should follow.

265
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:25,852
- Definitely not!
- Right.

266
00:11:25,935 --> 00:11:28,730
These days, if you talk to your teacher,

267
00:11:28,813 --> 00:11:30,440
they will take care of it.

268
00:11:30,523 --> 00:11:32,275
They'll write you notes and so on.

269
00:11:32,358 --> 00:11:34,027
It wasn't the right thing to do
at the time either.

270
00:11:34,110 --> 00:11:35,278
That's true. I got in trouble for it.

271
00:11:36,321 --> 00:11:37,447
Anyway, don't do what I did.

272
00:11:38,031 --> 00:11:39,032
But...

273
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:41,075
But...

274
00:11:41,159 --> 00:11:43,328
Won't this make the bookshop look bad?

275
00:11:43,411 --> 00:11:44,579
- Won't it?
- Well...

276
00:11:44,662 --> 00:11:46,331
All because of me.

277
00:11:46,831 --> 00:11:48,291
It's okay.

278
00:11:48,374 --> 00:11:50,335
You were a teenager back then.

279
00:11:50,418 --> 00:11:52,170
Teens rebel against their parents.

280
00:11:52,253 --> 00:11:54,881
You called it
"leaving to chase your dreams,"

281
00:11:54,964 --> 00:11:57,592
- but technically you ran away from home.
- You're right.

282
00:11:57,675 --> 00:11:59,510
So you headed to Seoul from Cheonan?

283
00:11:59,594 --> 00:12:01,679
Yes, I left my mom a letter,

284
00:12:01,763 --> 00:12:02,972
ran away from home,

285
00:12:03,056 --> 00:12:04,891
and went around auditioning.

286
00:12:04,974 --> 00:12:08,978
I ended up joining an idol agency.

287
00:12:09,062 --> 00:12:13,107
Back then, I wanted to be
a really cool K-pop idol.

288
00:12:13,191 --> 00:12:16,986
IDOL TRAINEE SUN-BIN
Who were your role models?

289
00:12:17,070 --> 00:12:17,987
- Role models?
- Yes.

290
00:12:18,071 --> 00:12:20,323
At the time, groups like 2NE1

291
00:12:20,406 --> 00:12:23,076
and Girls' Generation, you know?

292
00:12:23,159 --> 00:12:24,535
I wanted to be like them.

293
00:12:24,619 --> 00:12:27,247
You ran away from home
of your own free will.

294
00:12:27,330 --> 00:12:29,499
So you didn't ask your parents for money

295
00:12:29,707 --> 00:12:31,584
and had to support yourself.

296
00:12:31,668 --> 00:12:34,921
Yes, so I lived in the practice room.

297
00:12:35,672 --> 00:12:36,756
You had no home?

298
00:12:36,839 --> 00:12:39,634
I lived in a public sauna
for about a year and a half.

299
00:12:39,717 --> 00:12:43,471
I had my mom's long winter coat
in the practice room.

300
00:12:43,554 --> 00:12:45,598
I used that as a blanket at night.

301
00:12:45,682 --> 00:12:48,434
I put two couches together
to use as a bed.

302
00:12:48,518 --> 00:12:50,812
When I was a trainee in Seoul,

303
00:12:50,895 --> 00:12:55,149
I didn't have
the 5,400 won I needed to go home.

304
00:12:55,233 --> 00:12:57,360
Back then, the intercity bus

305
00:12:57,443 --> 00:13:00,196
from Seoul to Cheonan cost 5,400 won.

306
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:03,324
But because I couldn't
afford to pay that every single day,

307
00:13:03,825 --> 00:13:05,827
I decided to live in the practice room...

308
00:13:05,910 --> 00:13:08,079
- I have a question that's off-topic.
- Yes?

309
00:13:08,162 --> 00:13:10,290
Did you tell your mom
you were taking her coat?

310
00:13:10,373 --> 00:13:11,582
Of course.

311
00:13:11,791 --> 00:13:13,710
- You told her.
- Of course, I did.

312
00:13:14,836 --> 00:13:16,212
I wasn't that bad.

313
00:13:16,546 --> 00:13:18,172
Even though you just took off,

314
00:13:18,506 --> 00:13:20,133
- you told her you needed the coat.
- I did.

315
00:13:20,216 --> 00:13:21,968
Anyway, that was my situation.

316
00:13:22,051 --> 00:13:23,636
I remember back then,

317
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:27,974
the CEO gave me 10,000 won a day
because he felt sorry for me.

318
00:13:28,057 --> 00:13:31,519
The other trainees were from further away,
like Cheongju and Incheon.

319
00:13:31,602 --> 00:13:34,022
I was from Cheonan,
but I couldn't afford to go.

320
00:13:34,105 --> 00:13:35,773
There was a public sauna

321
00:13:35,857 --> 00:13:37,650
right across the practice room in Sinsa.

322
00:13:37,734 --> 00:13:38,943
It was for me to take a bath there.

323
00:13:39,193 --> 00:13:40,903
That's what the 10,000 won a day was for.

324
00:13:40,987 --> 00:13:43,156
- To take a bath?
- Yes.

325
00:13:43,239 --> 00:13:45,283
To take baths and not look homeless.

326
00:13:45,366 --> 00:13:48,328
Some investors would come
every now and then.

327
00:13:48,411 --> 00:13:49,495
So I had to look clean.

328
00:13:49,579 --> 00:13:50,997
When did he start giving you the money?

329
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:52,915
When I started living there.

330
00:13:53,458 --> 00:13:56,544
You know what, Hocrates?

331
00:13:56,627 --> 00:13:58,671
When I couldn't go to the sauna,

332
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:01,674
I would get hot drinking water
from the water purifier

333
00:14:01,758 --> 00:14:05,470
because the practice room bathroom
didn't have hot water.

334
00:14:05,553 --> 00:14:07,430
So I got it from the water purifier

335
00:14:07,513 --> 00:14:10,350
and mixed it with the cold water
to wash my hair.

336
00:14:10,433 --> 00:14:12,518
- Does that really work?
- Yes.

337
00:14:12,602 --> 00:14:13,811
You get better at it.

338
00:14:13,895 --> 00:14:15,980
- You get better at it?
- You do.

339
00:14:16,064 --> 00:14:19,192
Anyway, I saw an opportunity there.

340
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:21,736
It was 6,000 won to just use the shower

341
00:14:21,819 --> 00:14:23,321
and 8,000 won to sleep there.

342
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:24,781
So I saved up the change.

343
00:14:26,032 --> 00:14:28,159
I'd have over 10,000 won by the weekend.

344
00:14:28,242 --> 00:14:30,411
I used that for the bus
to and from Cheonan.

345
00:14:30,828 --> 00:14:32,580
The amazing thing is,

346
00:14:32,663 --> 00:14:34,916
I had to stay in the practice room longer

347
00:14:34,999 --> 00:14:36,709
because I couldn't afford

348
00:14:36,793 --> 00:14:38,503
to go back home, right?

349
00:14:38,586 --> 00:14:41,547
But that made me
improve a lot in a short period.

350
00:14:42,507 --> 00:14:46,511
Because all I could do was practice.

351
00:14:46,969 --> 00:14:49,555
Deficiency makes dreams
clearer and greater.

352
00:14:49,639 --> 00:14:51,224
I think that's true.

353
00:14:51,307 --> 00:14:53,726
You couldn't go home.

354
00:14:53,810 --> 00:14:56,813
- Back then, you had a kind of deficiency.
- Right.

355
00:14:56,896 --> 00:14:59,232
- Washing your hair like that.
- It made me feel awful

356
00:14:59,315 --> 00:15:00,566
and self-conscious.

357
00:15:00,650 --> 00:15:02,360
But that made your dream clearer.

358
00:15:02,443 --> 00:15:03,403
That's right.

359
00:15:03,486 --> 00:15:07,156
The stairway to my dream
became more solid.

360
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:08,658
It energized you.

361
00:15:09,117 --> 00:15:10,243
I think you're right.

362
00:15:10,326 --> 00:15:12,662
Then how did you end up becoming an actor?

363
00:15:13,079 --> 00:15:15,581
The company was in a bad situation

364
00:15:15,665 --> 00:15:17,750
so we had to part ways.

365
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:20,378
But even then, I don't think I gave up.

366
00:15:20,795 --> 00:15:23,089
I was freelancing as a model

367
00:15:23,172 --> 00:15:26,134
and also worked as a background actor.

368
00:15:26,217 --> 00:15:29,512
I would fill in for other people,
so to speak.

369
00:15:29,595 --> 00:15:31,764
There would be these background roles,

370
00:15:31,848 --> 00:15:34,225
not main but background roles,

371
00:15:34,308 --> 00:15:35,476
- that needed a stand-in.
- A stand-in.

372
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:38,229
They'd call me to fill in
and I'd run over.

373
00:15:38,312 --> 00:15:39,730
- So--
- In rehearsals?

374
00:15:39,814 --> 00:15:43,025
Yes, whenever they needed someone there
to set up the cameras

375
00:15:43,109 --> 00:15:45,278
when the main actors weren't available.

376
00:15:45,361 --> 00:15:47,280
- Like a body double.
- Yes, a body double.

377
00:15:47,363 --> 00:15:49,031
- I forgot the word.
- Body double.

378
00:15:49,115 --> 00:15:50,450
It happens.

379
00:15:50,533 --> 00:15:51,576
I forgot that word.

380
00:15:51,659 --> 00:15:52,952
I'm glad I remembered it for you.

381
00:15:53,035 --> 00:15:54,370
- I know. Thank you.
- Right.

382
00:15:54,454 --> 00:15:56,372
So, a body double...

383
00:15:56,456 --> 00:15:58,040
- Body double...
- It drives you nuts

384
00:15:58,124 --> 00:15:59,542
when you can't remember a word.

385
00:15:59,625 --> 00:16:01,002
- It makes me so mad.
- It does.

386
00:16:02,044 --> 00:16:03,754
"Body double" is such an easy word.

387
00:16:03,838 --> 00:16:04,881
I'm sorry.

388
00:16:06,299 --> 00:16:08,342
I'm sorry. I have to focus.

389
00:16:09,302 --> 00:16:11,846
I didn't want to say this to an actor,

390
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:13,931
but you're a bit goofier than I thought.

391
00:16:14,015 --> 00:16:15,641
I was trying to hide that today.

392
00:16:16,350 --> 00:16:17,518
I'm sorry.

393
00:16:18,561 --> 00:16:20,313
A director saw me.

394
00:16:20,396 --> 00:16:23,149
- The director shot a lot of ads
- The director.

395
00:16:23,232 --> 00:16:26,694
and told the CEO of the ad agency

396
00:16:26,777 --> 00:16:29,322
that I'd be worth investing in.

397
00:16:29,405 --> 00:16:31,866
The director talked me up to the CEO.

398
00:16:31,949 --> 00:16:34,535
"There's something charming about her

399
00:16:34,619 --> 00:16:36,704
- when she's on camera."
- I see.

400
00:16:36,787 --> 00:16:39,916
That led to me becoming an actor.

401
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:43,044
So I slowly started to audition

402
00:16:43,127 --> 00:16:45,171
and switched agencies.

403
00:16:45,338 --> 00:16:46,923
And now, here I am.

404
00:16:47,590 --> 00:16:49,717
That brings us back to the book.

405
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:52,637
If you were to thank the god

406
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:54,347
- for helping you,
- Yes?

407
00:16:54,430 --> 00:16:57,642
you'd thank the god
for sending such nice people.

408
00:16:57,725 --> 00:16:58,976
It's amazing, honestly.

409
00:16:59,060 --> 00:17:01,646
If you have the will,
a supernatural energy

410
00:17:01,729 --> 00:17:03,439
- seems to help you out.
- That's right.

411
00:17:03,523 --> 00:17:06,734
I first started doing musicals at church,

412
00:17:06,817 --> 00:17:09,487
and one of the teachers
was a musical theater actor.

413
00:17:09,570 --> 00:17:12,365
That person told me
about the audition opportunity.

414
00:17:12,448 --> 00:17:15,785
Come to think of it, that person
was like a divine entity in my life.

415
00:17:15,868 --> 00:17:17,370
The person gave me a hint.

416
00:17:17,453 --> 00:17:19,163
I also think

417
00:17:19,247 --> 00:17:21,832
that if I didn't work for it myself,

418
00:17:21,916 --> 00:17:23,751
I wouldn't have had the opportunity.

419
00:17:25,419 --> 00:17:27,505
Someone might hand me the opportunity,

420
00:17:27,588 --> 00:17:29,840
but whether or not I take it is up to me.

421
00:17:29,924 --> 00:17:32,552
I have to live the life to take it.

422
00:17:32,635 --> 00:17:35,638
Here's how I got all those gigs
as a background actor.

423
00:17:35,721 --> 00:17:37,431
I made my own profile

424
00:17:37,515 --> 00:17:39,559
with pictures taken with my phone.

425
00:17:39,642 --> 00:17:42,520
I went to all the agencies in Garosu-gil

426
00:17:42,603 --> 00:17:44,814
and put my profile in their mailboxes.

427
00:17:44,897 --> 00:17:47,024
That's how I got them to notice me.

428
00:17:47,108 --> 00:17:49,527
If I don't make a move,

429
00:17:49,610 --> 00:17:51,362
no one can do anything for me.

430
00:17:51,445 --> 00:17:54,240
Someone who was sent from above,
like an angel,

431
00:17:54,323 --> 00:17:55,950
could give me an opportunity,

432
00:17:56,033 --> 00:17:59,161
but if I'm not living my life
and going after it,

433
00:17:59,245 --> 00:18:01,330
I wouldn't be able to seize it.

434
00:18:01,956 --> 00:18:03,624
- Life
- Yes?

435
00:18:03,874 --> 00:18:06,711
would be easier
if it were just written in a book,

436
00:18:06,794 --> 00:18:08,504
but life is more complicated.

437
00:18:08,588 --> 00:18:09,797
- That's right.
- Right?

438
00:18:09,880 --> 00:18:13,134
It'd be nice to walk
knowing where you're going,

439
00:18:13,217 --> 00:18:14,302
but you have to start walking

440
00:18:14,385 --> 00:18:16,053
- without knowing.
- That's so true.

441
00:18:16,137 --> 00:18:19,140
All you can do is hope
the way you're going is the right way.

442
00:18:19,223 --> 00:18:21,934
Out of desperation,
because you can't do nothing,

443
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:24,020
- all you can do is just walk.
- Right.

444
00:18:24,103 --> 00:18:25,938
But you were out handing out your CV,

445
00:18:26,022 --> 00:18:27,440
- and you didn't stay put.
- Yes.

446
00:18:27,523 --> 00:18:29,150
You turned it into energy
that powered you.

447
00:18:29,233 --> 00:18:30,192
I think so.

448
00:18:30,276 --> 00:18:32,862
Whenever my friends
have a similar dilemma,

449
00:18:33,029 --> 00:18:34,739
I say, "Just go for it."

450
00:18:34,822 --> 00:18:36,616
I always tell them to go for it.

451
00:18:36,699 --> 00:18:37,950
I have a story.

452
00:18:38,034 --> 00:18:40,244
I have a close friend.

453
00:18:40,328 --> 00:18:43,289
That friend was preparing
for a design contest.

454
00:18:43,372 --> 00:18:46,751
They worked on it harder than anyone else.

455
00:18:46,834 --> 00:18:48,878
But they failed to meet the deadline.

456
00:18:49,420 --> 00:18:51,547
They were 30 minutes late.

457
00:18:51,631 --> 00:18:54,717
They just needed 30 more minutes,
but they couldn't finish it.

458
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:57,595
They did really well but gave up.

459
00:18:57,678 --> 00:18:59,805
Even then, I told them,

460
00:18:59,889 --> 00:19:01,641
"Don't give up like this.

461
00:19:01,724 --> 00:19:03,142
If you can't submit it,

462
00:19:03,225 --> 00:19:05,770
go to a different page of their website

463
00:19:05,853 --> 00:19:07,688
and show them what you did.

464
00:19:07,772 --> 00:19:09,857
It won't work, but still, just post it."

465
00:19:09,940 --> 00:19:12,777
They were like, "Why would they care?

466
00:19:12,860 --> 00:19:14,737
They won't even click on it."

467
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:16,822
But you know what happened?

468
00:19:17,490 --> 00:19:20,242
Of course, they didn't win.
They were late.

469
00:19:20,326 --> 00:19:23,788
But the company contacted them
and said it was impressive.

470
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:26,457
You see, they couldn't submit it in time.

471
00:19:26,540 --> 00:19:28,668
But still, even if it doesn't work out,

472
00:19:28,751 --> 00:19:31,087
if you show it, someone will notice.

473
00:19:31,170 --> 00:19:32,797
I think it's always like that.

474
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:35,508
So you can never give up.

475
00:19:36,342 --> 00:19:38,803
But couldn't they
just have been a bit faster?

476
00:19:38,886 --> 00:19:40,262
- It would've been better
- That's true.

477
00:19:40,346 --> 00:19:41,305
- It would've been better.
- if they turned it in faster.

478
00:19:41,389 --> 00:19:44,016
But even if you didn't make it,

479
00:19:44,100 --> 00:19:46,560
you shouldn't just give up like that.

480
00:19:46,644 --> 00:19:49,605
They wouldn't have gotten feedback
if they hadn't submitted at all.

481
00:19:49,689 --> 00:19:51,816
But look what happened.

482
00:19:51,899 --> 00:19:54,777
Your friend took action

483
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:56,987
knowing they could fail
and got experience.

484
00:19:57,071 --> 00:19:59,323
- They couldn't believe it, either.
- That's what happened.

485
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:01,200
They were surprised.

486
00:20:01,283 --> 00:20:05,079
I will always believe
in the power of action.

487
00:20:05,996 --> 00:20:07,248
Wow, that's crazy.

488
00:20:07,331 --> 00:20:09,208
You should never just stay put.

489
00:20:09,291 --> 00:20:12,086
- The door opened because you knocked
- Of course.

490
00:20:12,169 --> 00:20:13,587
- and didn't stay put.
- Yes.

491
00:20:13,671 --> 00:20:14,672
You didn't stay put!

492
00:20:14,755 --> 00:20:15,965
You still don't.

493
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:17,299
- Never!
- Right.

494
00:20:19,844 --> 00:20:24,432
I HELP EVERYONE, I'M EQUAL

495
00:20:24,515 --> 00:20:28,811
IN THE END, YOU MADE YOUR OWN CHOICES

496
00:20:30,271 --> 00:20:33,399
The god helps everyone equally.

497
00:20:34,024 --> 00:20:37,737
But what you see at the end of your life
is the result of your choices,

498
00:20:38,446 --> 00:20:42,491
whether it's a happy ending
or a bad ending.

499
00:20:42,742 --> 00:20:43,659
That's so powerful.

500
00:20:43,743 --> 00:20:45,661
- Do you remember this?
- Of course.

501
00:20:45,745 --> 00:20:47,580
I think what that line means is...

502
00:20:48,038 --> 00:20:52,042
To be honest, we often blame other people.

503
00:20:52,543 --> 00:20:54,503
- We have the urge.
- Yes.

504
00:20:54,587 --> 00:20:56,505
I do that, too.

505
00:20:56,589 --> 00:21:00,468
Some lives may seem great
and some may not seem that way,

506
00:21:00,551 --> 00:21:03,929
but at the moment of death,

507
00:21:04,013 --> 00:21:07,099
your choices are what make up your life.

508
00:21:07,183 --> 00:21:10,144
Whether it turns out
to be good or bad in the end.

509
00:21:10,227 --> 00:21:11,145
- Right.
- Yes.

510
00:21:11,228 --> 00:21:13,230
The way I see it,

511
00:21:13,314 --> 00:21:15,691
it seems like
you're the epitome of taking risks.

512
00:21:15,775 --> 00:21:19,236
But these attempts
don't always end with positive results.

513
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:20,529
- Yes, I've faced many failures.
- Right.

514
00:21:20,613 --> 00:21:22,072
Have you ever wanted to quit?

515
00:21:22,156 --> 00:21:23,908
So many times. Too many.

516
00:21:24,325 --> 00:21:27,328
The trainee period
that I mentioned before.

517
00:21:27,411 --> 00:21:28,913
That was something I've never done before.

518
00:21:29,288 --> 00:21:32,041
There have been many failures,
even in my acting career.

519
00:21:32,124 --> 00:21:35,294
Sometimes, I'll try something new
and aim to do it perfectly,

520
00:21:35,377 --> 00:21:37,630
but often it wouldn't be well-received.

521
00:21:38,172 --> 00:21:40,132
But you can't be scared of failure.

522
00:21:40,216 --> 00:21:41,258
- That's right. You can't.
- Right.

523
00:21:41,342 --> 00:21:43,719
If you take a risk and fail,

524
00:21:43,803 --> 00:21:44,887
you become stronger.

525
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:49,809
Honestly, I've learned
so much from failure.

526
00:21:50,643 --> 00:21:52,061
If you don't fail,

527
00:21:52,144 --> 00:21:54,605
you can only see what you're good at,

528
00:21:54,688 --> 00:21:56,565
and you stick with that.

529
00:21:56,649 --> 00:21:58,484
But if you fail over and over again,

530
00:21:58,567 --> 00:22:02,112
it opens your eyes
and broadens your horizons.

531
00:22:02,530 --> 00:22:04,615
The more you fail, the more you see.

532
00:22:04,907 --> 00:22:05,950
When you have a choice,

533
00:22:06,033 --> 00:22:08,369
- you should choose the hard way
- Right.

534
00:22:08,452 --> 00:22:10,621
- and fail spectacularly.
- Exactly.

535
00:22:10,704 --> 00:22:13,874
One of the most important challenges
you took on

536
00:22:13,958 --> 00:22:15,209
- is acting.
- Yes.

537
00:22:15,292 --> 00:22:16,752
<i>- Work Later, Drink Now.</i>
- Yes.

538
00:22:16,836 --> 00:22:18,963
Wow, now that I think of it,

539
00:22:19,046 --> 00:22:21,382
you've been in a lot of adaptations.

540
00:22:21,465 --> 00:22:22,299
That's right.

541
00:22:22,383 --> 00:22:23,843
I have the books...

542
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:25,302
I have them in my bookcase.

543
00:22:25,386 --> 00:22:28,097
- Which books?
- I prepared the books.

544
00:22:28,722 --> 00:22:31,433
- There they are.
- Oh, right.

545
00:22:32,017 --> 00:22:34,353
- These, right?
- Right.

546
00:22:34,436 --> 00:22:36,564
- The original work<i>, Drinker City Women.</i>
- Yes.

547
00:22:36,647 --> 00:22:37,940
- This...
- The three friends.

548
00:22:38,023 --> 00:22:40,734
Yes, this was actually also a webtoon.

549
00:22:42,820 --> 00:22:43,988
Yes.

550
00:22:44,071 --> 00:22:45,739
For any adaptation,

551
00:22:45,823 --> 00:22:47,533
- there are fans of the original work.
- That's right.

552
00:22:47,616 --> 00:22:49,702
- There must be a lot of pressure.
- There is.

553
00:22:49,785 --> 00:22:51,412
- That was the biggest issue.
- Of course.

554
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:53,038
It's a lot of pressure.

555
00:22:53,122 --> 00:22:55,666
The viewers have expectations,

556
00:22:55,749 --> 00:22:57,960
- but there are also regulations.
- Yes.

557
00:22:58,043 --> 00:22:59,169
- Because it's for TV,
- Right.

558
00:22:59,253 --> 00:23:00,754
- things get cut
- Right.

559
00:23:00,838 --> 00:23:03,215
- according to the regulations,
- Yes.

560
00:23:03,299 --> 00:23:05,718
- and it can feel a little flat.
- Right.

561
00:23:05,801 --> 00:23:07,469
- It happens.
- It must be upsetting when that happens.

562
00:23:07,553 --> 00:23:09,430
There are the opposite cases, too.

563
00:23:09,513 --> 00:23:12,725
When it's way too over-the-top
compared to the original.

564
00:23:12,808 --> 00:23:15,936
It can happen
when giving shape to a character.

565
00:23:16,020 --> 00:23:21,191
For adaptations, particularly ones
where there are high expectations,

566
00:23:21,275 --> 00:23:25,863
I try harder to understand
the original work better

567
00:23:25,946 --> 00:23:29,241
so I don't disappoint
fans of the original work.

568
00:23:29,325 --> 00:23:31,076
And there are fans of the original,

569
00:23:31,160 --> 00:23:32,912
- and fans of the series.
- Right.

570
00:23:32,995 --> 00:23:34,496
After watching the series,

571
00:23:34,580 --> 00:23:36,832
people who found it interesting

572
00:23:37,041 --> 00:23:39,084
will wonder what the original is like.

573
00:23:39,168 --> 00:23:41,211
They become interested in the original

574
00:23:41,295 --> 00:23:43,923
and a lot of them end up
reading the original.

575
00:23:44,006 --> 00:23:44,882
That's pretty cool.

576
00:23:44,965 --> 00:23:48,802
Look, the book
wouldn't have had this before.

577
00:23:48,886 --> 00:23:51,513
"The viral TV series,
<i>Work Later, Drink Now</i>."

578
00:23:51,597 --> 00:23:53,682
It would've just been the book.

579
00:23:53,766 --> 00:23:56,477
- But the series brings attention to it,
- Right.

580
00:23:56,560 --> 00:23:59,063
and people read the original.

581
00:23:59,146 --> 00:24:00,689
Series first, book next.

582
00:24:00,773 --> 00:24:02,107
- Yes.
- The other way around.

583
00:24:02,191 --> 00:24:04,735
Did you read the original work
before the script?

584
00:24:04,818 --> 00:24:06,403
No, I actually read the script first,

585
00:24:06,487 --> 00:24:08,614
and then read the original work.

586
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:10,991
Because when I'm reading the script,

587
00:24:11,075 --> 00:24:13,827
I'm reading it as an actor.

588
00:24:13,911 --> 00:24:17,539
But there are details that I need
that are not in the script,

589
00:24:17,623 --> 00:24:21,251
such as the way
this character acts and talks.

590
00:24:21,335 --> 00:24:23,128
So I read the original work
for those details,

591
00:24:23,212 --> 00:24:25,923
and extracted those character traits

592
00:24:26,006 --> 00:24:28,801
- I see.
- to project in my acting.

593
00:24:28,884 --> 00:24:31,303
It was challenging
working on <i>Work Later, Drink Now</i>

594
00:24:31,387 --> 00:24:33,472
- Right.
- because I'm a lightweight.

595
00:24:33,847 --> 00:24:35,432
It must've been difficult to play the role

596
00:24:35,641 --> 00:24:37,601
since you're actually
not much of a drinker.

597
00:24:37,685 --> 00:24:38,894
But you know what?

598
00:24:38,978 --> 00:24:41,063
People who can't handle alcohol

599
00:24:41,146 --> 00:24:44,108
get to see the process
of everyone at the table

600
00:24:44,191 --> 00:24:45,442
getting drunk.

601
00:24:45,526 --> 00:24:47,444
From when they're sober

602
00:24:47,528 --> 00:24:49,655
- until they're completely drunk.
- Exactly.

603
00:24:49,738 --> 00:24:52,616
Wasn't it also difficult
to swear like a sailor?

604
00:24:52,700 --> 00:24:53,909
Of course it was.

605
00:24:53,993 --> 00:24:56,161
I'm not even from the Jeolla area.

606
00:24:56,245 --> 00:24:58,831
I'm from Chungnam,
but I had to use their dialect.

607
00:24:58,914 --> 00:25:00,499
I had to pull off the dialect

608
00:25:00,582 --> 00:25:02,710
- and the profanity.
- The profanity.

609
00:25:02,793 --> 00:25:04,545
And I had to act with my whole face.

610
00:25:04,628 --> 00:25:06,338
Of all the lines,

611
00:25:06,422 --> 00:25:08,549
is there a line
that sticks with you even now?

612
00:25:08,632 --> 00:25:10,050
Like, "I'll twist you like twine,

613
00:25:10,134 --> 00:25:11,927
dice you until you're dead as a doornail,

614
00:25:12,011 --> 00:25:13,137
and smash and smack you some more"?

615
00:25:15,431 --> 00:25:16,932
It's not as if I wanted to memorize that.

616
00:25:17,016 --> 00:25:19,476
I memorized that line
for two and a half months,

617
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:22,521
so now, I can't get rid of it.

618
00:25:22,604 --> 00:25:24,565
- It just comes like that? Go!
- Yes.

619
00:25:24,648 --> 00:25:26,150
"I'll twist you like twine,

620
00:25:26,233 --> 00:25:28,110
dice you until you're dead as a doornail,

621
00:25:28,193 --> 00:25:29,903
and smash and smack you some more."

622
00:25:30,362 --> 00:25:32,281
I say, "I'll twist you like twine,"

623
00:25:32,364 --> 00:25:33,532
and the rest comes automatically.

624
00:25:33,615 --> 00:25:35,951
What scene is this line even from?

625
00:25:36,035 --> 00:25:37,161
- This line?
- Yes.

626
00:25:37,244 --> 00:25:39,830
It's the scene with Park Young-kyu.

627
00:25:40,289 --> 00:25:42,499
I get drunk

628
00:25:42,583 --> 00:25:45,461
- and rebel against him.
- I see.

629
00:25:45,544 --> 00:25:47,504
- Some curses sound offensive.
- Right.

630
00:25:47,921 --> 00:25:49,173
But this is satisfying.

631
00:25:49,256 --> 00:25:52,885
I think they wanted the line
to be punchy and catchy.

632
00:25:52,968 --> 00:25:54,595
Wow, that's amazing.

633
00:25:54,678 --> 00:25:56,805
It'll be useful
when you're on variety shows.

634
00:25:56,889 --> 00:25:57,931
- Is it?
- Yes.

635
00:25:58,015 --> 00:26:00,059
I watched a lot of your interviews.

636
00:26:00,142 --> 00:26:02,478
<i>- Work Later, Drink Now</i> was great,
- Right.

637
00:26:02,561 --> 00:26:04,438
- But so was <i>To the Moon</i>.
- Right.

638
00:26:04,521 --> 00:26:06,523
I saw an interview

639
00:26:06,607 --> 00:26:09,026
where you said
the character was just like you.

640
00:26:09,109 --> 00:26:10,861
That's what you said.

641
00:26:10,944 --> 00:26:14,198
DA-HAE, A NON-REGULAR HIRE
AT A CONFECTIONERY COMPANY,

642
00:26:14,281 --> 00:26:16,325
IS TIRED OF THE SAME-OLD REALITY

643
00:26:16,408 --> 00:26:18,911
WHEN A COLLEAGUE SUGGESTS
CRYPTO INVESTMENT

644
00:26:18,994 --> 00:26:21,663
IN THE PROCESS OF IT,
SHE FINDS WHAT SHE WANTS

645
00:26:22,289 --> 00:26:25,167
She's been through a lot of failure,

646
00:26:25,250 --> 00:26:28,796
but even in those hard times,

647
00:26:28,879 --> 00:26:31,715
she never stopped trying

648
00:26:31,799 --> 00:26:33,175
no matter what people say.

649
00:26:33,258 --> 00:26:36,136
At first, it shows her unfortunate life.

650
00:26:36,220 --> 00:26:38,597
- This series is about crypto, right?
- Right.

651
00:26:38,680 --> 00:26:40,349
Through crypto,

652
00:26:40,432 --> 00:26:42,184
she's looking for her "big break."

653
00:26:42,267 --> 00:26:43,435
That's what she wants.

654
00:26:43,519 --> 00:26:44,728
Was it Altcoin?

655
00:26:45,187 --> 00:26:47,189
I actually know nothing about crypto.

656
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:54,446
You said the character was literally you.

657
00:26:54,530 --> 00:26:57,616
I was just talking about
what the character is like.

658
00:26:57,699 --> 00:26:59,868
Even though you're not into crypto,

659
00:26:59,952 --> 00:27:01,662
shouldn't you try it
to get into character?

660
00:27:01,745 --> 00:27:03,205
I'm scared.

661
00:27:03,288 --> 00:27:04,414
You're scared?

662
00:27:04,498 --> 00:27:05,916
I'm bad at these things.

663
00:27:05,999 --> 00:27:08,043
- I have something to say.
- Yes?

664
00:27:09,086 --> 00:27:11,672
Some things you go for,
some things you don't.

665
00:27:13,632 --> 00:27:14,716
Be cautious.

666
00:27:16,426 --> 00:27:17,970
When it comes to investing--

667
00:27:18,053 --> 00:27:19,346
Who were you talking to?

668
00:27:19,429 --> 00:27:20,973
Me? The viewers.

669
00:27:21,723 --> 00:27:23,600
How do you invest your money then?

670
00:27:24,643 --> 00:27:25,644
Recently,

671
00:27:26,186 --> 00:27:28,438
I got really into gold.

672
00:27:28,897 --> 00:27:30,357
I got into it.

673
00:27:30,440 --> 00:27:32,568
I'm looking into gold.

674
00:27:32,776 --> 00:27:34,403
- Looking into gold?
- Yes.

675
00:27:34,862 --> 00:27:37,614
So you need to be cautious of crypto--

676
00:27:37,698 --> 00:27:40,617
- Gold is a secure asset.
- Is it?

677
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:42,369
It's a secure asset.

678
00:27:42,452 --> 00:27:45,122
But it's not like I'm planning on

679
00:27:45,205 --> 00:27:47,040
- making it big with gold.
- Right.

680
00:27:47,124 --> 00:27:49,126
- May I say something?
- Sure.

681
00:27:49,209 --> 00:27:50,294
Be cautious.

682
00:27:51,170 --> 00:27:53,380
- I don't go big.
- Are you being cautious?

683
00:27:53,463 --> 00:27:54,965
- I am.
- Are you?

684
00:27:55,048 --> 00:27:56,508
- Are you going all-in?
- No.

685
00:27:56,592 --> 00:27:57,593
Are you diversifying?

686
00:27:57,676 --> 00:27:58,844
Not even that.

687
00:27:58,927 --> 00:28:00,512
The only way
I'm taking care of my finances

688
00:28:00,596 --> 00:28:02,556
- is by looking into gold.
- Taking care of your finances.

689
00:28:02,639 --> 00:28:04,558
- Looking into gold.
- Looking into gold.

690
00:28:06,185 --> 00:28:09,396
- There's a reason behind this.
- What's the reason?

691
00:28:09,479 --> 00:28:11,648
Is it okay? It's not related to the book.

692
00:28:11,732 --> 00:28:13,233
- Of course. Why not?
- Well...

693
00:28:13,317 --> 00:28:15,986
Here's the reason
why I started looking into gold.

694
00:28:16,069 --> 00:28:19,364
Someone gifted me some gold
a long time ago.

695
00:28:19,448 --> 00:28:22,117
How many grams was it?
It's in the shape of a turtle.

696
00:28:22,201 --> 00:28:24,077
- It's a turtle.
- That's pretty big.

697
00:28:24,161 --> 00:28:26,038
- It's only this big.
- I see.

698
00:28:26,121 --> 00:28:28,749
Anyway, I forgot where I even put it.

699
00:28:28,832 --> 00:28:32,211
But I found it while I was cleaning.

700
00:28:32,294 --> 00:28:34,338
I was like, "Right, I had this!"

701
00:28:34,421 --> 00:28:36,757
When I opened it,
a piece of paper fell out.

702
00:28:36,840 --> 00:28:38,467
- I opened it.
- The certificate of authenticity.

703
00:28:38,550 --> 00:28:41,929
Yes, and it said it was 18.75g.

704
00:28:42,387 --> 00:28:44,765
- A <i>don</i> is 3.75g.
- Right.

705
00:28:44,848 --> 00:28:47,893
So it was around six <i>don</i>.

706
00:28:47,976 --> 00:28:51,939
And it also had the price
at the time of the purchase.

707
00:28:52,022 --> 00:28:54,524
It said it was 1.63 million won.

708
00:28:54,608 --> 00:28:55,901
- At the time.
- Yes.

709
00:28:55,984 --> 00:28:59,696
So I looked up the current price,
guessing it might be up by 50,000 won.

710
00:29:00,739 --> 00:29:03,116
And it was over four million won.

711
00:29:03,200 --> 00:29:04,993
It's almost quadruple the amount.

712
00:29:05,619 --> 00:29:07,704
So how could I not be interested in gold?

713
00:29:08,205 --> 00:29:09,581
Do you still have it?

714
00:29:09,665 --> 00:29:11,124
- The turtle?
- Yes.

715
00:29:11,208 --> 00:29:12,417
Of course.

716
00:29:12,501 --> 00:29:14,086
- It should be higher now.
- Yes.

717
00:29:14,169 --> 00:29:15,629
I'm not sure about the latest price,

718
00:29:15,712 --> 00:29:17,839
but it's probably over 4.5 million.

719
00:29:17,923 --> 00:29:21,385
It's about six <i>don.</i>

720
00:29:21,468 --> 00:29:22,928
- We looked it up.
- Okay.

721
00:29:23,011 --> 00:29:24,096
Six <i>don</i>

722
00:29:24,554 --> 00:29:26,807
is currently 5.19 million won.

723
00:29:27,975 --> 00:29:31,520
FOOTNOTE: THAT'S ON THE DAY OF THE SHOOT,
AND IT'S HIGHER NOW

724
00:29:32,938 --> 00:29:34,523
Look at that.

725
00:29:34,606 --> 00:29:38,026
I last checked the price
before <i>To the Moon</i>.

726
00:29:38,777 --> 00:29:40,195
While shooting <i>To the Moon</i>,

727
00:29:40,279 --> 00:29:43,240
- my character was into crypto,
- Into crypto.

728
00:29:43,323 --> 00:29:44,992
but in real life, I was investing in gold.

729
00:29:46,076 --> 00:29:47,744
So, Lee Sun-bin

730
00:29:48,161 --> 00:29:50,497
went to the moon with gold.

731
00:29:50,580 --> 00:29:51,957
I'm not on the moon yet.

732
00:29:52,040 --> 00:29:53,542
I'm trying to go to the moon.

733
00:29:53,625 --> 00:29:56,753
Come on, it already rose
four to five times.

734
00:29:56,837 --> 00:29:59,131
I have to start
collecting little by little.

735
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:00,924
All right.

736
00:30:01,383 --> 00:30:04,052
EVERYONE DESERVES TO ENJOY BETTER THINGS

737
00:30:04,136 --> 00:30:07,097
THERE'S NO ONE IN THE WORLD WHO DOESN'T

738
00:30:07,180 --> 00:30:10,142
THAT GOES THE SAME FOR YOU, ME, AND MY MOM

739
00:30:10,225 --> 00:30:13,186
FROM <i>TO THE MOON</i>

740
00:30:14,062 --> 00:30:16,023
- I think it's called "taking a risk"
- Right.

741
00:30:16,106 --> 00:30:17,983
because you're doing something
despite the risks.

742
00:30:18,066 --> 00:30:19,484
It's not a risk if it's something easy.

743
00:30:19,568 --> 00:30:21,361
- Right.
- It's challenging to take risks.

744
00:30:22,237 --> 00:30:23,280
I mean...

745
00:30:23,655 --> 00:30:26,325
You took a risk
when you revealed that you were dating.

746
00:30:26,408 --> 00:30:28,452
IS HAVING YOUR RELATIONSHIP
KNOWN TO THE PUBLIC TAKING A RISK?

747
00:30:28,535 --> 00:30:30,954
- It requires courage.
- That was smooth.

748
00:30:31,038 --> 00:30:32,539
A relationship known to the public...

749
00:30:32,998 --> 00:30:34,791
- I wouldn't consider it taking a risk.
- It wasn't?

750
00:30:34,875 --> 00:30:35,959
Not at all.

751
00:30:36,043 --> 00:30:38,670
- Dating publicly--
- It was a choice.

752
00:30:38,754 --> 00:30:41,089
- As opposed to dating privately--
- "I'm going to date publicly!"

753
00:30:41,173 --> 00:30:42,716
- It's not like I was like that.
- Right.

754
00:30:42,799 --> 00:30:46,636
But you could've kept it
between the two of you.

755
00:30:46,720 --> 00:30:48,138
- You mean I could've hid it.
- Right.

756
00:30:48,221 --> 00:30:49,556
It didn't have to be public.

757
00:30:49,639 --> 00:30:52,142
But I never thought of it
as taking a risk.

758
00:30:52,225 --> 00:30:56,229
I think deciding to start the relationship
was a challenge in itself.

759
00:30:56,313 --> 00:30:58,023
Right? Do you know what I mean?

760
00:30:58,106 --> 00:30:59,191
I see.

761
00:30:59,274 --> 00:31:00,650
Deciding to date...

762
00:31:00,734 --> 00:31:02,152
- That was the challenge.
- Right.

763
00:31:02,652 --> 00:31:03,820
Don't you agree?

764
00:31:03,904 --> 00:31:05,113
That's what's challenging.

765
00:31:05,655 --> 00:31:07,366
And you succeeded.

766
00:31:07,449 --> 00:31:10,577
It being public wasn't up to me,

767
00:31:10,660 --> 00:31:12,120
but it came out.

768
00:31:12,204 --> 00:31:14,498
From there,
it took courage to make a choice.

769
00:31:15,749 --> 00:31:17,125
It was cute what you did
at the award show.

770
00:31:17,209 --> 00:31:19,878
I can't help being silly.

771
00:31:19,961 --> 00:31:21,338
Did you want to see him better?

772
00:31:21,421 --> 00:31:25,467
After that, I thought I'd get in trouble.

773
00:31:25,550 --> 00:31:28,053
- With... Yes.
- With the public and the fans?

774
00:31:28,553 --> 00:31:30,472
I thought I'd be in trouble
for being silly there.

775
00:31:30,555 --> 00:31:32,224
It was my first time being invited

776
00:31:32,307 --> 00:31:33,975
to the Blue Dragon Film Awards.

777
00:31:34,059 --> 00:31:35,519
So how did everyone react to it?

778
00:31:35,602 --> 00:31:38,230
Everyone was so supportive.

779
00:31:38,313 --> 00:31:40,816
- What did they say?
- They thought it was cute.

780
00:31:40,899 --> 00:31:42,818
I'm actually not a cute person.

781
00:31:43,276 --> 00:31:45,195
I'm not really on the cute side.

782
00:31:45,612 --> 00:31:47,656
But they thought so.

783
00:31:47,739 --> 00:31:49,074
I'll never do that pose again though.

784
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:54,329
- In the future,
- Yes?

785
00:31:54,413 --> 00:31:59,418
is there a genre you would like to try?

786
00:31:59,501 --> 00:32:02,421
Oh, this year,

787
00:32:02,504 --> 00:32:04,756
I got to do a genre that I wanted.

788
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:06,967
We're in the preparation stage.

789
00:32:07,509 --> 00:32:10,679
Whenever someone asked me
this question in an interview last year,

790
00:32:10,762 --> 00:32:13,723
I always said
that I wanted to do an action film.

791
00:32:13,849 --> 00:32:16,601
And now I get to fight with swords.

792
00:32:16,685 --> 00:32:18,019
- A period drama.
- Yes.

793
00:32:18,103 --> 00:32:20,313
- The lines won't be easy.
- I know.

794
00:32:20,397 --> 00:32:23,066
- There should be a lot of tricky words.
- Exactly.

795
00:32:23,150 --> 00:32:25,152
I know you have a problem with words.

796
00:32:25,235 --> 00:32:26,570
A big problem.

797
00:32:28,488 --> 00:32:30,407
- I even forgot "body double."
- What is it called?

798
00:32:30,490 --> 00:32:33,326
It's called
<i>The Sword: Rebirth of the Red Wolf</i>.

799
00:32:33,410 --> 00:32:35,162
Kim Han-min will be directing.

800
00:32:35,245 --> 00:32:37,789
- He directed <i>Roaring Currents!</i>
- Yes.

801
00:32:37,873 --> 00:32:40,709
That's his next film,

802
00:32:40,792 --> 00:32:42,210
and I get to do action in it.

803
00:32:42,294 --> 00:32:44,254
- You're an actor, right?
- Yes.

804
00:32:44,337 --> 00:32:47,132
I heard that actors are people
who never stop learning.

805
00:32:47,215 --> 00:32:48,341
That's so true.

806
00:32:48,425 --> 00:32:49,843
For every new project,

807
00:32:49,926 --> 00:32:51,261
you learn something new.

808
00:32:51,344 --> 00:32:53,305
- That's right.
- You learn a new way of life.

809
00:32:54,139 --> 00:32:55,223
That reminds me.

810
00:32:55,307 --> 00:32:57,392
While shooting<i> Criminal Minds</i>,

811
00:32:57,809 --> 00:32:59,644
through watching Son Hyun-joo,

812
00:32:59,728 --> 00:33:01,563
I really learned

813
00:33:01,855 --> 00:33:05,025
how to create
a pleasant atmosphere on set.

814
00:33:05,108 --> 00:33:06,359
He remembers everyone's names.

815
00:33:06,443 --> 00:33:07,819
- Yes, and he's so friendly.
- Right.

816
00:33:08,236 --> 00:33:10,572
Even with the youngest staff members,

817
00:33:10,655 --> 00:33:12,908
he always approaches first
and is so polite.

818
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:14,910
- He approaches first?
- Always.

819
00:33:14,993 --> 00:33:16,411
He's always smiling,

820
00:33:16,495 --> 00:33:18,330
and he rarely gets upset.

821
00:33:18,413 --> 00:33:20,957
"I want to be as amazing as him."

822
00:33:21,333 --> 00:33:23,210
I thought that so many times.

823
00:33:23,293 --> 00:33:25,212
How about Kim Hye-soo?

824
00:33:26,505 --> 00:33:27,464
- I mean...
- Yes?

825
00:33:27,964 --> 00:33:32,469
When I was literally just starting out
as barely even a rookie...

826
00:33:33,094 --> 00:33:35,347
It must've been around 2015.

827
00:33:35,430 --> 00:33:37,390
- That's ten years ago.
- Right.

828
00:33:37,474 --> 00:33:40,685
I worked on a film called <i>Familyhood</i>.

829
00:33:40,769 --> 00:33:42,729
I had a minor role,

830
00:33:42,812 --> 00:33:44,981
but I had to directly interact with her

831
00:33:45,065 --> 00:33:47,609
and work closely together.

832
00:33:47,692 --> 00:33:51,488
We had to physically fight
and scream at each other in the scene.

833
00:33:51,571 --> 00:33:52,822
And she was like...

834
00:33:52,906 --> 00:33:54,658
Because she didn't know me,

835
00:33:54,741 --> 00:33:57,494
I said, "Hello, I'm actor Lee Sun-bin."

836
00:33:57,577 --> 00:33:59,204
I introduced myself to her.

837
00:33:59,621 --> 00:34:02,541
The first thing she said
after she said hi was this.

838
00:34:02,624 --> 00:34:05,210
"Hold on, I have to grab you

839
00:34:05,293 --> 00:34:07,420
and fight you later.

840
00:34:07,504 --> 00:34:09,214
I'm scared I'm going to hurt you."

841
00:34:09,297 --> 00:34:12,884
And then she went off to clip her nails.

842
00:34:13,260 --> 00:34:15,011
- Because she didn't want to hurt me.
- Oh my.

843
00:34:15,095 --> 00:34:16,680
Just so I wouldn't get hurt.

844
00:34:16,763 --> 00:34:19,057
And she taught me how to grab her

845
00:34:19,140 --> 00:34:21,142
and pretend-fight.

846
00:34:21,226 --> 00:34:24,688
I learned what it's like

847
00:34:24,771 --> 00:34:30,026
when someone cares
about the person they're acting with.

848
00:34:30,110 --> 00:34:32,028
When it comes to learning,

849
00:34:32,112 --> 00:34:35,407
you actually learn a lot
from bad examples, too.

850
00:34:35,490 --> 00:34:36,908
- Like a cautionary tale.
- Yes.

851
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:39,953
- "I shouldn't do that."
- I see bad examples on set

852
00:34:40,036 --> 00:34:42,163
and learn a lot from them.

853
00:34:42,247 --> 00:34:44,624
But I can't talk about them here
on television.

854
00:34:46,209 --> 00:34:48,336
Cautionary tales can be very educational.

855
00:34:48,420 --> 00:34:49,588
- They're the best.
- Right.

856
00:34:49,671 --> 00:34:51,089
"I shouldn't do that."

857
00:34:53,842 --> 00:34:55,677
You learn a lot from those.

858
00:34:56,511 --> 00:34:59,973
A lot of people say you're someone
who doesn't forget her roots.

859
00:35:00,056 --> 00:35:01,725
That's what people say.

860
00:35:01,808 --> 00:35:04,144
People also say

861
00:35:04,227 --> 00:35:05,979
that you're a good person at heart.

862
00:35:06,062 --> 00:35:07,981
How do you feel about this?

863
00:35:08,064 --> 00:35:09,733
I'm so grateful.

864
00:35:09,816 --> 00:35:12,652
I'm grateful that
there are many good people

865
00:35:12,736 --> 00:35:16,990
who view me as being myself
and acting without pretense

866
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,867
in a positive light.

867
00:35:18,950 --> 00:35:21,911
- I heard there was a book that made you
- Yes?

868
00:35:21,995 --> 00:35:23,538
perceive people with love.

869
00:35:23,622 --> 00:35:26,708
- Oh, the book that I read?
- Yes.

870
00:35:26,791 --> 00:35:28,835
- It's a collection of poems.
- A collection of poems?

871
00:35:28,918 --> 00:35:30,211
It's a book of poems.

872
00:35:30,295 --> 00:35:32,380
I think what's more powerful

873
00:35:32,464 --> 00:35:34,341
is reading one sentence
that I resonate with

874
00:35:34,424 --> 00:35:36,760
than reading pages of grandiose words.

875
00:35:37,093 --> 00:35:38,094
That's what I think.

876
00:35:38,678 --> 00:35:40,805
- I believe in that too.
- Me too.

877
00:35:40,889 --> 00:35:42,766
- There's a saying about that.
- Right.

878
00:35:42,849 --> 00:35:46,603
The book is called
<i>Morning Postcards by Ahn Do-hyun</i>.

879
00:35:47,062 --> 00:35:48,188
I read it,

880
00:35:48,688 --> 00:35:51,900
and there were many great poems

881
00:35:51,983 --> 00:35:53,735
that teach you a lot about life.

882
00:35:53,818 --> 00:35:56,404
Could you pick a stanza you like

883
00:35:56,488 --> 00:35:58,198
- and read it for us?
- Yes.

884
00:35:58,281 --> 00:36:00,075
- I like this part.
- We'd love that.

885
00:36:02,118 --> 00:36:06,081
"Everything exists for this world.

886
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:11,127
It seems like there is nothing
that does not exist for this world.

887
00:36:12,045 --> 00:36:15,840
Therefore, there is nothing to waste
in this world."

888
00:36:16,841 --> 00:36:17,884
I love that stanza.

889
00:36:17,967 --> 00:36:19,928
Let's say I don't like someone.

890
00:36:20,011 --> 00:36:22,597
I would think there must be
a reason behind their actions.

891
00:36:22,972 --> 00:36:24,891
You start understanding them.

892
00:36:24,974 --> 00:36:26,976
I was in Jeju

893
00:36:27,060 --> 00:36:28,728
- shooting the film <i>Sumbisori.</i>
- Yes.

894
00:36:28,812 --> 00:36:31,064
- It's about <i>haenyeo</i>, female divers.
- Yes.

895
00:36:31,147 --> 00:36:34,567
When we'd rest between takes,
we'd sit on a big rock in the water,

896
00:36:34,651 --> 00:36:35,902
splashing each other,

897
00:36:35,985 --> 00:36:38,321
saying, "Look at all these sea anemones!

898
00:36:38,405 --> 00:36:41,783
They're good for nothing
but being slippery!" but jokingly.

899
00:36:42,158 --> 00:36:44,202
And one <i>haenyeo</i> said to me

900
00:36:44,285 --> 00:36:45,912
while laughing,

901
00:36:45,995 --> 00:36:47,956
"They're not good for nothing.

902
00:36:48,415 --> 00:36:52,836
Every living thing in the ocean
is good for something."

903
00:36:53,795 --> 00:36:56,548
And that reminded me of this.

904
00:36:56,631 --> 00:36:58,091
That really shook me.

905
00:36:58,174 --> 00:37:02,053
Just because I think it's good for nothing

906
00:37:02,762 --> 00:37:04,848
and I don't know why it exists,

907
00:37:04,931 --> 00:37:09,269
that doesn't mean there's a reason
it shouldn't exist in this world.

908
00:37:09,352 --> 00:37:10,186
Right.

909
00:37:11,187 --> 00:37:13,356
- In this world... Right?
- That touched me.

910
00:37:13,440 --> 00:37:15,817
I still don't know
what use sea anemones have.

911
00:37:15,900 --> 00:37:18,069
- We might think they're useless.
- Exactly.

912
00:37:18,153 --> 00:37:20,113
- But to someone, it might not be.
- Yes.

913
00:37:20,196 --> 00:37:22,365
That hit me like a ton of bricks.

914
00:37:23,616 --> 00:37:24,784
I LOVE PEOPLE

915
00:37:24,868 --> 00:37:26,995
THEY'D BE SO HAPPY
IF THEY LOVED EACH OTHER

916
00:37:27,078 --> 00:37:27,954
HAHA

917
00:37:28,037 --> 00:37:30,498
YOU LEARN SOMETHING FROM EVERYONE,
EVEN THREE-YEAR-OLDS

918
00:37:30,582 --> 00:37:32,876
IF THREE PEOPLE GATHER,
YOU'LL LEARN FROM ONE OF THEM

919
00:37:33,501 --> 00:37:35,044
This question...

920
00:37:35,545 --> 00:37:38,089
- is the last one from the epilogue.
- Okay.

921
00:37:38,173 --> 00:37:40,508
Here at <i>Hodong's Bookshop</i>,

922
00:37:40,592 --> 00:37:43,094
we read your story,
and this is the last question for you.

923
00:37:43,178 --> 00:37:46,556
Sun-bin, what kind of ending
will you show us?

924
00:37:46,639 --> 00:37:47,807
- Me?
- Yes.

925
00:37:47,891 --> 00:37:48,850
THE ENDING THAT SUN-BIN WANTS

926
00:37:48,933 --> 00:37:52,645
I want to show the ending
that people look forward to.

927
00:37:52,729 --> 00:37:54,939
- I see.
- I still expect a lot from myself.

928
00:37:55,023 --> 00:37:56,858
I'm still very ambitious.

929
00:37:56,941 --> 00:37:59,360
So project after project,

930
00:37:59,444 --> 00:38:01,029
I want people to think,

931
00:38:01,696 --> 00:38:03,156
"What will she do next?

932
00:38:03,239 --> 00:38:04,824
- I'm looking forward to it."
- Right.

933
00:38:04,908 --> 00:38:08,369
That's the best compliment
an actor could ask for.

934
00:38:08,453 --> 00:38:11,539
An actor who makes us
look forward to her next move.

935
00:38:11,831 --> 00:38:15,502
I don't know about other people,
but I look forward to your future.

936
00:38:15,668 --> 00:38:17,921
I feel so supported.

937
00:38:19,339 --> 00:38:20,882
I was nervous about today.

938
00:38:21,508 --> 00:38:23,468
- Variety shows must want you.
- They really do.

939
00:38:25,345 --> 00:38:28,598
How do you reject or manage
all of those requests?

940
00:38:28,681 --> 00:38:31,100
There seem to be more requests
from variety shows than from films.

941
00:38:31,184 --> 00:38:33,520
If I were a variety show producer,
I'd want you on the show.

942
00:38:33,603 --> 00:38:34,896
- You think so?
- Yes.

943
00:38:35,647 --> 00:38:37,357
I don't know how this will sound.

944
00:38:37,440 --> 00:38:38,733
Even when I'm looking at you,
I want to see more.

945
00:38:39,943 --> 00:38:42,237
I'm a "Feeling" type. Don't do that.

946
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:45,031
- Sorry?
- That's so touching.

947
00:38:45,114 --> 00:38:46,324
I'm getting emotional.

948
00:38:46,407 --> 00:38:48,701
I'm sorry,
but that was the title of a song.

949
00:38:49,035 --> 00:38:50,328
Sorry about that.

950
00:38:51,496 --> 00:38:53,540
"EVEN WHEN I SEE YOU, I WANT TO SEE MORE"
BY SON HYUN-JOO

951
00:38:53,623 --> 00:38:55,041
ORIGINALLY SUNG BY KWON YOON-KYONG

952
00:38:55,959 --> 00:38:57,418
- I've been--
- You're amazing.

953
00:38:57,502 --> 00:38:59,128
I've been feeling

954
00:38:59,212 --> 00:39:01,756
particularly emotional lately!

955
00:39:02,382 --> 00:39:03,633
It was a song.

956
00:39:03,716 --> 00:39:05,593
It was even sung by Son Hyun-joo,
who we talked about earlier.

957
00:39:05,677 --> 00:39:06,636
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

958
00:39:08,137 --> 00:39:10,431
- I have a question.
- Yes?

959
00:39:10,515 --> 00:39:11,683
What is it?

960
00:39:11,766 --> 00:39:15,979
So how much will you pay for my book?

961
00:39:17,188 --> 00:39:18,940
The price

962
00:39:19,941 --> 00:39:21,150
of Lee Sun-bin's book...

963
00:39:21,860 --> 00:39:22,819
It has been decided!

964
00:39:22,902 --> 00:39:24,153
How much?

965
00:39:24,237 --> 00:39:27,323
The price of
Lee Sun-bin's favorite book is...

966
00:39:30,201 --> 00:39:32,245
<i>The Life Before Us!</i>

967
00:39:32,328 --> 00:39:33,913
- Sorry?
<i>- The Life Before Us!</i>

968
00:39:35,582 --> 00:39:36,457
Okay?

969
00:39:37,083 --> 00:39:37,917
Wait.

970
00:39:38,001 --> 00:39:40,169
I'm sorry, but I didn't get that.

971
00:39:41,421 --> 00:39:42,297
What did you say?

972
00:39:43,423 --> 00:39:45,633
<i>The Life Before Us.</i>

973
00:39:45,717 --> 00:39:47,051
The Life...

974
00:39:47,135 --> 00:39:48,344
- Before Us!
- Before Us.

975
00:39:49,596 --> 00:39:52,015
<i>- The Life Before Us.</i>
<i>- The Life Before Us.</i>

976
00:39:52,098 --> 00:39:53,182
- Let me explain.
- Okay.

977
00:39:53,266 --> 00:39:54,183
A BOY LEARNING TO LOVE LIFE
WHILE MAINTAINING DIGNITY IN POVERTY

978
00:39:54,267 --> 00:39:57,312
"A person can't live without love.

979
00:39:57,729 --> 00:39:59,522
You endured the hard times,

980
00:39:59,898 --> 00:40:01,107
and you kept going.

981
00:40:01,190 --> 00:40:03,568
You filled that time up
with love and passion

982
00:40:03,651 --> 00:40:05,904
and built a life
that shines like it does now."

983
00:40:06,613 --> 00:40:08,323
Just like the protagonist Momo,

984
00:40:08,948 --> 00:40:13,328
I hope your future
will be full of people and love.

985
00:40:15,538 --> 00:40:18,333
I, Hocrates, will be rooting for you.

986
00:40:18,917 --> 00:40:21,336
Thank you.

987
00:40:22,337 --> 00:40:25,048
- This is Emile Ajar's book,
- Yes.

988
00:40:25,131 --> 00:40:28,426
<i>The Life Before Us</i>. It's my gift to you.

989
00:40:28,509 --> 00:40:31,554
I think people will be your fans forever
after this interview.

990
00:40:33,932 --> 00:40:36,142
What do you regret the most about today?

991
00:40:36,225 --> 00:40:38,853
Is there something
you wish you hadn't said?

992
00:40:38,937 --> 00:40:39,771
Let's see...

993
00:40:39,854 --> 00:40:40,855
Everything?

994
00:40:46,027 --> 00:40:47,946
This is <i>Hodong's Bookshop,</i>

995
00:40:48,404 --> 00:40:50,949
in the cutest neighborhood in the world,

996
00:40:51,032 --> 00:40:52,867
Kangho-dong.

997
00:40:52,951 --> 00:40:55,203
We heard about
Lee Sun-bin's tasty life today.

998
00:40:55,286 --> 00:40:58,289
That was a great read!

999
00:40:58,623 --> 00:40:59,499
Hello.

1000
00:40:59,582 --> 00:41:01,876
- Oh my.
- Hello. I'm here to sell a book.

1001
00:41:01,960 --> 00:41:03,336
This is a good workout.

1002
00:41:03,419 --> 00:41:06,422
No matter how difficult things are,
you can overcome them with positivity.

1003
00:41:06,506 --> 00:41:08,383
- No matter what.
- Say that it rains.

1004
00:41:08,466 --> 00:41:10,134
It's fine by me. I like it.

1005
00:41:10,218 --> 00:41:11,177
Even during a match.

1006
00:41:11,260 --> 00:41:13,805
